      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Leviticus 8:13",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Leviticus 8:13",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") for the head-dress of Aaron’s sons. He describes fully another mitre with a triple golden crown. This was probably an ornament added in later times. Alexander Balas sent a purple robe and a crown of gold to Jonathan which he wore at the Feast of Tabernacles b.c. 153 (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Ma 10:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). This may be the crown described by Josephus.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "upon the mitre, in front",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] In A.V. ‘upon his forefront,’ ‘his’ refers to the mitre and in modern English would be ‘its.’",
        "children": []
